Rebasing means that we increase the quantity by printing more money in the
 underlying smart contract to increase.
 Simply put, if at the end of some period (the 
\emph on
rebase period
\emph default
) the price has increased by an average X%, all we need to do is change
 the coin supply by an average X%: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\Delta P & =\frac{P'-P}{\bar{P}}\\
\Delta Q & =\frac{Q'-Q}{\bar{Q}}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

Note that we measure price and quantity changes (
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta Q$
\end_inset

) as relative to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

settlement averages
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{P}=(P'+P)/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{Q}=(Q'+Q)/2$
\end_inset

 in the denominator).
 This convention allows us to more easily analyze changes as is shown in
 the following example.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\series bold
Example:
\series default
 let's say that we simply used the face value price change 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta P=\frac{P'-P}{P}$
\end_inset

 .
 A price change from $1 to $1.4 would translate to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta P=40\%$
\end_inset

, whereas a price change back from $1.4 to $1 would translate to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta P=\$0.6-\$1=-28\%$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
If we use the settlement average price change as suggested before, we would
 get a 33% change in both directions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta P=\Delta Q$
\end_inset

 we find the solution to the target quantity
